shared_text:
Sundown Lane Elementary School
September 11 at 1:26 PM ·

Dear Sundown Lane Parents,

As you know, September 11th is Patriot Day. Typically, our PTA would help us to host our annual Patriot Day program. Even though we weren't able host parents at our school, we did want to celebrate Patriot Day on our campus, and invite parents to participate.
Special thanks to Ms. Nevarez, our Music teacher, for teaching our students The Star Spangled Banner, Grand Old Flag, and Fifty Nifty. Ms. Nevarez recorded each grade level singing these songs and posted the videos to our SeeSaw classes. Parents, please look in your SeeSaw class message for this video from Ms. Nevarez.
We hope you enjoy seeing your kids perform these songs for Patriot Day!

TEA and Canyon ISD are requesting parents/guardians to screen their students daily. If your child has any of the following symptoms, please contact your school. Share the responsibility and keep everyone safe.

GO: What's Your Plan
August 6 at 1:11 PM ·

Do you like to work with your hands, interacting with people, and following procedures? If so, you could be a great surgical technologist! In our area, surgical techs typically earn $20/hour, and you can get your certificate at Amarillo College in just 3-4 semesters. AC is enrolling now! Learn more: https://www.actx.edu/surg_tech/index.php, or call 806.371.5440 to meet with an advisor virtually. Don't forget to download #GoPlan2.0 (https://goplan.life/goplan2-0.html ) to help you succeed in earning your surgical tech certification.

#NLNE #ittakesavillage #wearelimitless #goplanyourlife

Face Shields - The Texas Education Agency has changed from their original stance about clear face shields as a preventive.

Registration Reminders - We have a larger number of unregistered former students as compared to the same time period last year (2 weeks before the first day). I'm urging parents to complete the registration process. https://youtu.be/oHZ9huXgd20

post_text: Canyon ISD Board of Trustees is pleased to appoint Matt Parker as the interim Trustee for Place 5 board vacancy. Mr. Parker has experience in professional leadership roles on various community boards providing a broad exposure to non-profit, for profit, and government entities. Mr. Parker is the Vice President of Cardiovascular Services at BSA Hospital. Mr. Parker and his wife, Valerie have two children, a 2020 graduate and another student in high school.

post_text: Governor Greg Abbott extended the application deadline for the federal Pandemic-Electronic Benefit Transfer program (P-EFT) to July 31. P-EBT is a one-time benefit of $285 per eligible child and can be used in the same ways as Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) food benefits to pay for groceries. Visit hhs.texas.gov/pebt to learn more about P-EBT. For question regarding eligibility, call 833-613-6220.

post_text:
Our plans in CISD are to have students and staff return to the school buildings in August. However, we know that a portion of our families may have concerns about returning to school due to COVID .

This past week, school districts received guidance from the Texas Education Agency (who oversees school districts) regarding virtual schooling. The requirements for virtual school are significantly more demanding on students daily participation and completion of work at home, as compared to this past spring. Based on these new requirements, we have started discussions about how we will prepare for and build our plan to manage the demands for School@Home instruction.

School districts have not received guidance from the Texas Education Agency on requirements for students and staff returning to the school buildings in August. We are hoping to hear this information any day.

Once we learn more about the options for starting school in August, our team in Canyon ISD will communicate our plans to our teachers as well as our parents.

post_text:
It has been a priority that Canyon ISD honors the class of 2020, and we are very proud of how our seniors forged forward and completed their senior year during these unexpected times. This season of COVID uncertainties altered a traditional graduation due to restrictions by the Texas Governor. Following our virtual graduation experience, Canyon ISD emailed our seniors to ask if they would participate in an outdoor ceremony.

The District notified the community about the survey through an online video, and an automated phone message sent to senior parents and guardians. The results of the survey showed that only 27% of the combined senior class responded yes they would attend an outdoor graduation ceremony. Due to a low level of interest and participation, Canyon ISD will not be planning an outdoor graduation.

For the convenience of Canyon ISD families and students, we have provided the virtual graduations online, and they are available for download cisd.us/graduation.

Here is today's video:
https://youtu.be/7tWvNd1LrtM

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
Andrea Cochran, Behavior Intervention Coordinator, shared some parenting tips on Canyon ISD's video last Monday.
Key Concepts in building a schedule
1. Address 4 areas to a balanced life: Work/School Time, Family Time, Community/Service Time, and Leisure/Hobby Time.
2. Add times of waking up, bedtime, and meals.
3. Post the schedule for all to see and follow.
4. It may be necessary to have checkboxes to show progress.

Key Concepts in building a schedule

3. Post the schedule for all to see and follow.
4. It may be necessary to have checkboxes to show progress.

Practica el distanciamiento social

Para prevenir la propagación de COVID-19 en nuestra comunidad, practique el distanciamiento social:
• Evite salir en público
• Cuando esté en público, mantenga una distancia de seis pies entre usted y los demás.
• Seguir las recomendaciones de los funcionarios locales y estatales.
Obtenga más información en https://texas.gov/covid19
# covid19 #texasfuerte #quedateencasa

Practice Social Distancing

To avoid the spread of COVID-19 in our community, practice social distancing:
• Avoid going out in public
• When in public, keep six feet of distance between you and others
• Follow guidance provided by local and state officials.
Get more information at https://texas.gov/covid19
#covid19 #texasstrong #stayhome

post_text: Canyon ISD takes the safety of our community and our students very seriously. To address community concern, we are sharing expectations communicated to the CHS students who took a trip to NYC. This trip was not a school sponsored trip. When they returned to Canyon on Monday, March 16th, the Canyon ISD administration recommended, due to community concern, the students self quarantine for 14 days.

post_text:
Thank you for your patience as we have been working through the excess of information about the global health concerns of the COVID-19 virus. Our first priority continues to be the health and safety of all our students, staff, and community. After collaborating with local districts, state and county health officials throughout the day, the District has decided to close March 23rd – 27th, along with the cancellation of all extracurricular activities. Staff will report to work for planning and professional development. Ultimately, our goal for school closure is to help prevent the spread of COVID-19. We will continue to update our website as additional information becomes available, specifically the plan developed for the return of students to school.
https://youtu.be/dlr4bkbNDsE
